The paper presents a method for solving Markov decision processes (MDPs) with large state spaces, which is a common problem in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The method involves partitioning the state space, which is related to work in data mining (cs.DM) and automata theory (cs.SY). The paper also introduces a new notion of a "bounded parameter MDP" (BMDP), which is related to work in programming languages (cs.PL) and optimization. Overall, the paper's focus on MDPs and optimization suggests that it is most likely to belong to cs.AI or cs.LG, but its connections to other subfields make it possible that it could also be classified under cs.DM, cs.SY, or cs.PL.
